{
  "texts": [
    "We deduce thatn-2+2g α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) = Γ C Γ n-3+3g I=1 δ f Γ I, (4.8)where the {f Γ I } are the constraints that pick out each of the covering maps in moduli space [6,9] and we acknowledge the possibility of non-trivial Jacobians from the delta functions by changing from C Γ to C Γ.",
    "It is understood that the proposed equality (4.8) holds in the context of the moduli space integral of (4.7).",
    "Of course, whilst the case C Γ = 0 does not give rise to the sampling property, one expects C Γ ̸ = 0 for non-trivial physicswe note that this has not been proven here or elsewhere in the literature to our knowledge.",
    "Finally, to maintain the full generality of the solution (4.8), we should consider the solution as an equivalence class of distributions, where two distributions are equivalent if they differ only on a set of measure zero and by a finite amount at these points.",
    "This is why the possibility of D({x i, w i, z i }) being finite but non-zero at points where a covering map exists is contained in (4.8).Our insertion of the operator e -Σ even allows for a quick method to derive the recursion relation of [7,9], which provides a constraint on the dependence of C Γ on the parameters {m i 1, m i 2 }."
  ]
}